              <tr> 
                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">A Guide To Weapons</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a2.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=2140"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=2140"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=5670">Eric "SmooveGroove" Carter</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 5670 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Lightsabers are a common weapon in both light and dark decks, but so many other weapons are overlooked when in fact they are a game-winning mechanic.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">       Chances are, if you&amp;#8217;re reading this you need some help with weapons. So what&amp;#8217;s the big deal with weapons you ask? Weapons are the key to defeating characters of any power and any ability. Want to get rid of Jedi Luke? *Impossible*, you say. Not at all. When you are finished with this article, you&amp;#8217;ll have a new lease on the power of weapons.<br>
	Let us examine some of the basic weapons that should be included in a Dark deck. A lightsaber is almost a definite hit, but you only get to use it once. Possibly the best dark side weapon is the Light Repeating Blaster Rifle. It deploys for 2 force, and may target using 2 force. The best part about this weapon is it is destiny +1&gt; than ability and allows you to fire repeatedly if a power droid or fusion generator present. Deploy a Portable Fusion Generator and it is destiny +2&gt; than ability, and lets you fire repeatedly for 2 force each time. This basically guarantees a hit on any character of ability of 4 or less. I&amp;#8217;m sure this weapon is looking pretty decent, but when it really shines is when you stack your deck with multiple cards of destiny 6 or greater. Combine that with Dr. Evazan and the Special Edition Boba Fett and every character you hit is forfeit=0 and immediately lost. Watch the expression of your opponent&amp;#8217;s face when you have two or three characters take out his Jedi Luke, Obi-Wan, Capt. Han and Chewbacca and end up having them immediately lost and worth nothing. With the right modification&amp;#8217;s to your deck, this weapon will let you take out any pesky rebel scum causing trouble.<br>
	Another great weapon for the Dark side to use is Bossks Mortar Gun. During a battle, draw destiny, if that destiny &gt;0, one card at that site is lost. Great way to get rid of all of those rebels with destinies of 1. A must in every deck because it doesn&amp;#8217;t require you to draw destiny greater than ability. It&amp;#8217;s essentially a hit every time.<br>
	Zuckuss&amp;#8217; Snare Rifle is a great way to capture low ability characters. It is destiny -1&gt; ability, but when targeting rebels with ability 1 or 2, all you have to pull is a 3 or 4. Definitely earns it&amp;#8217;s place in a dark deck for the value of capturing high forfeit rebels like Chewbacca and other low ability characters.<br>
	Yet again, another crown jewel of any dark deck would be Boba Fett&amp;#8217;s Blaster Rifle. Not only does it deploy as a react, but you may fire repeatedly for 1 force each time! Don&amp;#8217;t be afraid to force drain with Boba Fett alone anymore, simply stack your deck with lots of destiny 6 cards, save some force to fire, and lay waste to an unsuspecting opponent. While it does not have the same advantages as the Light Repeating Blaster Rifle, mainly it is only destiny&gt; ability, it is very useful in a fight to take care of many minor lightside characters. If you are looking for a fight, be sure to bring Boba Fett&amp;#8217;s Blaster Rifle with you.<br>
	Easily the riskiest weapon to use would be the Thermal Detonator. I would use this only if I knew I was going to lose the battle. It let&amp;#8217;s you draw three destiny, all cards with those destiny numbers are lost. The problem with this card is that you also risk killing your own characters, instead of just your opponents. Definitely has incredible carnage points, but I would only use it as a last ditch defense. Worth including simply for the fact that it can decimate your opponents characters.<br>
	One of the newer weapons for the dark side is the Force Pike. With a destiny of 4 and adding 1 to defense value it is a great addition to any deck. Not to mention the fact that it is destiny +1&gt;0.  With a deploy of 3 on a warrior other than a royal guard, it is a bit expensive, but you opponent will definitely feel the sting of this blade! It is great to use along with Royal Guards, Myn Kyneugh and Kir Kanos. Not as good as a repeating blaster, but it has great potential.<br>
<br>
	I see a lot of light side decks now that use a fairly limited range of weapons. The standard lightsabers are effective, but on the whole most people don&amp;#8217;t use a wide range of weapons in their light side decks. Perhaps you will think twice about putting some of the following in.<br>
	Perhaps the greatest weapon for the lightside is the Concussion Grenade. Big carnage points. Draw destiny, all cards with that destiny number are lost. With the addition of Sergeant Junkin, all of your characters are immune to the grenade and he can either subtract 1 or add 1 to the destiny. Many of the most powerful dark side characters have a destiny of 1, so this weapon has an incredibly potential, not to mention it can bring down AT-ATs and AT-STs. Considering the use of Electro-Binoculars, this weapon should be easy to pull off, leaving your opponent wondering what just happened. This should be included in any lightside deck that plans to battle, which should be every deck. <br>
	One of, if not *the* best lightside weapons would be the BlasTech E-11B Blaster Rifle. This little spitfire can pack quite a punch if used effectively. The main drawback to this weapon is it must be deployed on a scout warrior, but with the wide use of Jedi Luke and Luke Skywalker, Rebel Scout, it shouldn&amp;#8217;t be hard to have a farm-boy from Tatooine ripping through Imperials like old people at a buffet. Best of all, it allows you to fire repeatedly for 2 force each time. If you&amp;#8217;re trying to be economical, throw a couple of these in and throw out all of the main characters weapons, these will end up saving you in the long run if you stack some high destinies in your deck. Put in the fact that it is common, this weapon ranks at the top of my list for lightside choices. Great with your scout characters and Blast The Door Kid, which means all of your opponents characters with ability&gt;2 have to sit this battle out while you blast away at his little guys left behind to bear the brunt of your now superior forces! Great trick to pull on decks with high ability.<br>
	Anakins Lightsaber and Lukes Lightsaber are both great additions to a deck that plays any one of the various Luke personas. Best of all, Anakins Lightsaber can deploy on Princess Leia or Daughter or Skywalker while Luke can have his own laser toy. Best advantage of Lukes Lightsaber is that it gives a defense value increase of 1. This means that Jedi Luke is now power 8, defense value 7. <br>
	The Medium Repeating Blaster Cannon is tough to use, but great for getting rid of minor characters. May target up to 2 characters, if destiny &gt; total ability, they are hit. Want to get rid of Darth Vader? Use the MRBC and draw 2 destiny. Deploy it on Captain Yutani and he adds 1 to each destiny and can move it for free. Great addition to the lightsides limited amount of powerful weapons.<br>
	<br>
	Philosophy behind weapons. Now that you have your weaponry, you must provide your ammunition. Your ammunition is the destinies in your deck that you will be drawing. Providing destinies of 5 or 6 is the best option. There are many cards on both sides that have high destinies and are still useful. Putting 20 cards with destiny 6 may sound a bit ridiculous, but you are guaranteed to kill anything and everything you want. Stacking your deck with high destinies simply ensures that you will hit what you want to hit and not be let down by that destiny 0 we&amp;#8217;ve all pulled just when we needed it. I no longer take that risk and stock as many high destinies as possible because it is far better to know you will kill your opponents character, than to sit back and hope you pull the right destiny when you need it. When you use weapons in a battle, use them correctly and they won&amp;#8217;t let you down. Hopefully, you have been able to see the advantages of using some of the more unusual weapons and can take something useful out of this article and apply it to your deck.<br>
 </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=2140"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=2140"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?article=2140" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> </td>
